cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.DS, cs.GT, cs.AI. 

The paper deals with predicting edges in networks, which is a problem in social network analysis. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of algorithms and computational methods, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of game theory in the approach suggests that it could belong to the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category. The use of centrality measures and interaction indices suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the use of fast algorithms and evaluation on real-world networks suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.
